    "body": "QR codes are awesome, they are offline portal through which mobile devices access the online world. \r\n\r\nIn the context of status they are incredibly important because they provide a quick and easy way to connect with an other status user and potentially public chat, Dapp and perhaps in the near future private chats. \r\n\r\nConnections are important because the more connections a user has in a chat app the more useful the app becomes. The inverse is also true that a user of chat app with no connections does not find the app very useful because there is no one to chat to. \r\n\r\nThis importance of quick and easy connections in an offline environment is accentuated during conferences and meet ups like ETHIndia, ETHBerlin and the many to follow. \r\n\r\nThe update proposal is: \r\n\r\n1. Status QR code scanner can handle all QR codes which begin with status universal link patterns (directly linked to issue). \r\n\r\n2. Global “Scan QR code” button \r\n\r\n<img width=\"375\" alt=\"screen shot 2018-08-10 at 14 40 39\" src=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/7915365/43961631-6d30f380-9cad-11e8-9ede-f418f29766e8.png\">\r\n\r\nThese updates leverage the principle of letting the software do the heavy lifting. A user should not have to know to scan a specific QR code from a specific path. For example having to scan a personal contact QR code from a “scan QR code” button. If a user should scan public chat QR code via the “add new contact”, it should work for the user, not disrupting their intention. \r\n\r\nThe exception to this rule is transaction based QR codes which should only be scannable from the “send transaction” flow to make sure users do not accidentally attempt sending money to a contact QR code. \r\n\r\nIf the QR code can work across universal links and adding new connections increase Status app utility, then it should not be tucked 3 levels deep but behind the plus button.",
